entry.summary:
Day 1: Calorie Counting
https://adventofcode.com/2022/day/1 TL;DR: my solution in Rust We're on an expedition with the elves. 1000 2000 3000
4000
5000 6000
7000 8000 9000
10000
Find the Elf carrying the most Calories. For each elf we want to calculate the sum of the items they are carrying. I did today with one iterator chain. Get the input string. For every element: split on a single linebreak. Now, every element is the sum a single elf is carrying. pub fn part_1() -> u32 { let input = std::fs::read_to_string("src/day01.txt").unwrap();
input .split("\n\n") .map(|elf| { elf.lines() .filter_map(|s| s.parse::<u32>().ok()) .sum::<u32>() }) .max() .unwrap() }
Part 2 is very similar. Find the top three Elves carrying the most Calories. Get the input string. For every element: split on a single linebreak. Now, every element is the sum a single elf is carrying. To sort the iterator directly, I used the sorted() method from the itertools crate. .collect() on the iterator of all sums, and store that result in a variable with type Vec<u32>. .sort(). This sorts in ascending order, and I want the sum of the 3 last ones. use itertools::Itertools;
pub fn part_2() -> u32 { let input = std::fs::read_to_string("src/day01.txt").unwrap();
input .split("\n\n") .map(|elf| { elf.lines() .filter_map(|s| s.parse::<u32>().ok()) .sum::<u32>() }) .sorted() .rev() .take(3) .sum::<u32>() }
